  <title>Description</title>
  <titlealts>
    <searchtitle>NHS Business Definition: Unitary Authority - Description</searchtitle>
  </titlealts>
  <body>
  <div>
      <p>
A 
              <xref outputclass="businessDefinition"
               keyref="business_definition_unitary_authority">Unitary Authority</xref>
 (<xref outputclass="businessDefinition"
               keyref="business_definition_unitary_authority">UA</xref>) is a 
              <xref outputclass="class" keyref="class_geographic_area">GEOGRAPHIC AREA</xref>.        </p>
      <p>
         <xref outputclass="businessDefinition"
               keyref="business_definition_unitary_authority">Unitary Authorities</xref>
 are areas with a single tier of local government (as opposed to the two-tier 
              <xref outputclass="businessDefinition" keyref="business_definition_county">County</xref>:
              <xref outputclass="businessDefinition" keyref="business_definition_district">District</xref>
 structure). They are found wholly in Wales and parts of England.        </p>
      <p>
For further information on 
              <xref outputclass="businessDefinition"
               keyref="business_definition_unitary_authority">Unitary Authorities</xref>, see the 
              <xref outputclass="businessDefinition"
               keyref="business_definition_office_for_national_statistics">Office for National Statistics</xref>
 website at: 
              <xref href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/census/2001censusandearlier/glossary/ou"
               scope="external"
               format="html">Glossary</xref>.        </p>
  </div>
